\
The XP-58 (Xprinter XP-58 / POS-58 series) is fully ESC/POS compatible. The cash drawer opens by sending a single short command sequence directly to the printer (the printer then pulses the RJ11 cash drawer port). No text, no paper feed needed \'97 just the raw bytes.\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 Exact cash drawer open command for XP-58\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 Use this byte sequence (the most reliable one listed specifically for XP-58 / XP-58iii models):\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 Hex:
\f0\b0  
\fs30 1B 70 00 19 FA
\fs26 \uc0\u8232 
\f1\b Decimal:
\f0\b0  
\fs30 27, 112, 0, 25, 250
\fs26 \
In code, this is usually written as a byte array:\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs24 \cf0 // Java / Kotlin (Android)\
byte[] openDrawer = new byte[] \{\
    0x1B, 0x70, 0x00, 0x19, (byte)0xFA\
    // or decimal: (byte)27, (byte)112, (byte)0, (byte)25, (byte)250\
\};\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs26 \cf0 This is the standard 
\fs30 ESC p m t1 t2
\fs26  command where:\
\pard\pardeftab560\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f3\fs18 \cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f0\fs26 m = 0 (drawer pin 2 \'97 the one used on almost all XP-58 setups)\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f3\fs18 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f0\fs26 t1 = 25, t2 = 250 (pulse timing that works reliably on this model)\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Some printers accept slight variations (e.g. 
\fs30 1B 70 00 3C 78
\fs26  or 
\fs30 1B 70 00 60 120
\fs26 ), but the 25/250 version is confirmed to work on XP-58 series.\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 How to send it from your custom app (easiest options with RawBT already paired)\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 Since you already have RawBT installed and the XP-58 paired via Bluetooth (as per the green steps), you have two simple paths. You 
\f1\b do not need to reinvent Bluetooth connection
\f0\b0  \'97 let RawBT handle it.\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 Option 1: Use RawBT Intents (simplest, no extra port/server needed)\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 RawBT supports direct integration from other Android apps via Intents. Your app just sends the raw bytes to RawBT, and it forwards them over Bluetooth.\
See the official integration guide: https://rawbt.ru/intents.html\uc0\u8232 (It\'92s only a few lines of code \'97 basically start an Activity with the byte data and printer name.)\
This is the cleanest for a pure Android app.\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 Option 2: Use the \'93Server for RawBT\'94 companion app (this is probably what the green instructions meant by \'93HTTP port\'94)\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 Install the free 
\f1\b Server for RawBT
\f0\b0  from Google Play (package: 
\fs30 rawbt.server
\fs26 ).\uc0\u8232 It turns RawBT into a local network service with:\
\pard\pardeftab560\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f3\fs18 \cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f0\fs26 Raw TCP port 
\f1\b 9100
\f0\b0  (direct ESC/POS printing \'97 very common)\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f3\fs18 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f0\fs26 WebSocket API on port 
\f1\b 40213
\f0\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Your custom app (or even a web app on the same tablet) can then connect to 
\fs30 http://127.0.0.1:9100
\fs26  or the WebSocket and send the byte array above.\uc0\u8232 This matches the \'93find the HTTP port\'94 step in the green message (older versions sometimes showed ~8080; current is 40213/9100).\
Once the server is running and the printer is selected in RawBT, just open a socket and write the bytes.\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 Option 3: Direct Bluetooth from your app (more code, but possible)\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 If you don\'92t want to depend on RawBT at all, your app can open a BluetoothSocket to the paired XP-58 (UUID 
\fs30 00001101-0000-1000-8000-00805F9B34FB
\fs26 ) and write the bytes directly. But this is more work (permissions, connection handling, etc.). RawBT is usually the better bridge.\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

