\f1\b\fs32 \cf0 Why it works\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs26 \cf0 Your custom app and RawBT are both running on the 
\f1\b same Android device
\f0\b0  (the tablet). RawBT acts as a 
\f1\b print bridge
\f0\b0  for Bluetooth-connected printers like your XP-58. Your app can communicate with RawBT without any network or external server.\
The two easiest and most reliable ways for your Google Play app to open the cash drawer:\
\pard\pardeftab560\sa40\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs32 \cf0 1. Best option: Use RawBT Intents (Recommended \'97 simplest code)\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs26 \cf0 RawBT provides a built-in 
\f1\b Intent
\f0\b0  system so any other Android app (including yours from Google Play) can send raw ESC/POS bytes directly to it.\
Here is the exact ready-to-use Kotlin code (or Java equivalent) to open the cash drawer:\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs24 \cf0 // In your Activity or Fragment\
fun openCashDrawer() \{\
    val intent = Intent("ru.a402d.rawbtprinter.action.PRINT_RAWBT")\
    intent.setPackage("ru.a402d.rawbtprinter")  // Ensures it goes to RawBT\
\
    // Cash drawer command for XP-58 (most reliable version)\
    val drawerCommand = byteArrayOf(\
        0x1B, 0x70, 0x00, 0x19, 0xFA.toByte()   // ESC p 0 25 250\
    )\
\
    intent.putExtra("ru.a402d.rawbtprinter.extra.DATA", drawerCommand)\
    // Optional: specify your printer name if you have multiple\
    // intent.putExtra("ru.a402d.rawbtprinter.extra.PRINTER", "XP-58")\
\
    try \{\
        startActivity(intent)\
        // Success - RawBT will forward the command over Bluetooth to your XP-58\
    \} catch (e: Exception) \{\
        // Handle error (e.g. RawBT not installed)\
        // You can show a message: "Please install RawBT from Google Play"\
    \}\
\}\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

